systematized and applied.

29:46.000 --> 29:48.000
As for Barris Skinner,

29:48.000 --> 29:55.000
he, based on the developed methods,

29:56.000 --> 29:57.000
developed approaches,

29:58.000 --> 30:06.000
created a very extensive tool for influencing behavior.

30:07.000 --> 30:08.000
As for Skinner,

30:09.000 --> 30:14.000
he actually highlighted a new type of behavior

30:14.000 --> 30:18.000
that was not considered in psychology and science before.

30:19.000 --> 30:21.000
This is so-called operant behavior.

30:22.000 --> 30:23.000
What is it?

30:24.000 --> 30:29.000
Since our task is to analyze the practical application,

30:30.000 --> 30:31.000
we will not go into details,

30:32.000 --> 30:33.000
the main thing is that we have an understanding.

30:34.000 --> 30:38.000
There are two types of behavior.

30:39.000 --> 30:42.000
This is respondent behavior and operant behavior.

30:42.000 --> 30:45.000
As for respondent behavior,

30:46.000 --> 30:51.000
it is a well-known Pavlovian term,

30:52.000 --> 30:53.000
conditional reflexes.

30:54.000 --> 30:59.000
Skinner calls this type of training S,

31:00.000 --> 31:02.000
to emphasize the importance of stimulus.

31:03.000 --> 31:04.000
This is a stimulus training.

31:05.000 --> 31:06.000
S stands for the word stimulus.

31:07.000 --> 31:12.000
Accordingly, there is an old good tradition of behaviorism.

31:13.000 --> 31:16.000
There are external stimuli that affect the human body.

31:17.000 --> 31:18.000
There is a reaction of a person to these stimuli.

31:19.000 --> 31:21.000
Stimulus and reaction are respondent behaviors.

31:25.000 --> 31:28.000
It exists, it was perfectly considered by Pavlov.

31:29.000 --> 31:32.000
Skinner actually believed that after Pavlov,

31:33.000 --> 31:34.000
there was nothing else to do in respondent behavior.

31:34.000 --> 31:35.000
He discovered everything that was necessary.

31:36.000 --> 31:41.000
As for Skinner, he was a practitioner.

31:42.000 --> 31:45.000
The main thing for him was to get a practical result.

31:46.000 --> 31:48.000
This is what is characteristic of all behaviorism.

31:49.000 --> 31:54.000
In this regard, he was quite cool about theory.

31:55.000 --> 31:57.000
Because theory is our idea of ​​the scheme.

31:58.000 --> 31:59.000
Skinner was a behaviorist.

32:00.000 --> 32:03.000
He was not interested in what was in our heads.

32:04.000 --> 32:07.000
He was interested in the results we achieve.

32:08.000 --> 32:11.000
He was interested in the behavior of a person.

32:12.000 --> 32:13.000
We will not get into the head.

32:14.000 --> 32:17.000
Because this is a very subjective thing.

32:18.000 --> 32:20.000
But we will always see what a person does,

32:21.000 --> 32:22.000
how successful he is at it,

32:23.000 --> 32:24.000
what he succeeds and what he fails.

32:25.000 --> 32:27.000
We can study behavior objectively.

32:28.000 --> 32:29.000
Therefore, let's study it.

32:30.000 --> 32:33.000
But we will leave everything that is in the head to the psychologist.

32:34.000 --> 32:38.000
This was the idea that Skinner fully supported.

32:41.000 --> 32:43.000
As for Pavlov's respondent training,

32:44.000 --> 32:48.000
this is a training that really exists.

32:49.000 --> 32:55.000
It is inherent in both humans, animals, rats, mice, and worms.

32:56.000 --> 32:58.000
The main thing is to have a nervous system.

32:59.000 --> 33:02.000
If there is a nervous system that reacts to stimuli from the outside world,

33:02.000 --> 33:05.000
it gives a certain reaction.

33:06.000 --> 33:09.000
Accordingly, after the stimulus is exerted, there is a certain reaction.

33:10.000 --> 33:16.000
But Skinner thought about the fact that human behavior,

33:17.000 --> 33:18.000
I draw your attention again, is about behavior,

33:19.000 --> 33:21.000
not about the psyche, not about thinking.

33:22.000 --> 33:24.000
This will be a lot of cognitive approach.

33:25.000 --> 33:27.000
What we will consider further after Skinner.

33:28.000 --> 33:31.000
Skinner was based on the fact that a person behaves somehow.

33:32.000 --> 33:33.000
A person does something.

33:35.000 --> 33:41.000
Is there a difference in human behavior from animal behavior?

33:43.000 --> 33:45.000
Since for Skinner as a behaviorist,

33:46.000 --> 33:50.000
this entire inner psychological life was uninteresting,

33:51.000 --> 33:53.000
he did not deny it, he just did not deal with it.

33:54.000 --> 33:58.000
Accordingly, Skinner drew attention to the fact that

33:59.000 --> 34:02.000
a person, like other higher animals,

34:03.000 --> 34:06.000
does not only react to external stimuli.

34:07.000 --> 34:09.000
A person has a certain behavior.

34:10.000 --> 34:11.000
What does this behavior do?

34:12.000 --> 34:13.000
What does a person do?

34:14.000 --> 34:15.000
What does an animal do?

34:16.000 --> 34:20.000
We do it to get some kind of reactions,

34:20.000 --> 34:25.000
because these reactions give certain consequences.

34:26.000 --> 34:29.000
Either the consequences are positive for the body,

34:30.000 --> 34:32.000
we went there, found food,

34:33.000 --> 34:38.000
we did a job, got a material reward,

34:39.000 --> 34:41.000
we took the initiative, we were scolded.

34:42.000 --> 34:49.000
Accordingly, human behavior leads to various consequences.

34:51.000 --> 34:55.000
And then a person looks at these consequences.

34:56.000 --> 35:01.000
If these consequences are positive for a person,

35:02.000 --> 35:08.000
then Skinner says that this human behavior

35:09.000 --> 35:14.000
that leads to the consequences that suit a person,

35:15.000 --> 35:17.000
is behavior with reinforcement.

35:18.000 --> 35:19.000
I am satisfied with the result.

35:20.000 --> 35:25.000
Therefore, I build a certain line of behavior

35:26.000 --> 35:29.000
in order to then get a certain result.

35:30.000 --> 35:32.000
I know that to get a result,

35:33.000 --> 35:35.000
you need to take a certain number of steps.

35:36.000 --> 35:38.000
It can be long, it can be short.

35:39.000 --> 35:44.000
This sequence of steps can be complex,

35:45.000 --> 35:46.000
it can be simple.

35:47.000 --> 35:48.000
It can trigger different reactions,

35:48.000 --> 35:49.000
different schemes of behavior,

35:50.000 --> 35:51.000
different behavior programs.

35:52.000 --> 35:53.000
This term, by the way, is Skinner's,

35:54.000 --> 35:56.000
because Skinner, as we have already discussed,

35:57.000 --> 35:59.000
considering the methodology of organizational behavior,

36:00.000 --> 36:02.000
introduced the concept of programmed learning.

36:03.000 --> 36:05.000
So, Skinner said that human behavior

36:06.000 --> 36:10.000
is a certain program that he implements.

36:11.000 --> 36:15.000
And therefore, this program has the consequences

36:15.000 --> 36:19.000
of behavior that leads to the consequences that suit me.

36:20.000 --> 36:23.000
And, accordingly, if I want to get these consequences,

36:24.000 --> 36:27.000
then these consequences reinforce my behavior.

36:28.000 --> 36:30.000
And there are consequences that do not suit me.

36:31.000 --> 36:33.000
That is, if I do something,

36:34.000 --> 36:35.000
I will get an undesirable result.

36:36.000 --> 36:38.000
If I am constantly late for work, I will be fired.

36:39.000 --> 36:41.000
If I want to be fired,

36:42.000 --> 36:44.000
then I will be late and I will be fired,

36:45.000 --> 36:46.000
and it is the fault of the management.

36:47.000 --> 36:48.000
So, they fired me.

36:49.000 --> 36:50.000
If I do not want to be fired,

36:51.000 --> 36:53.000
I must change my behavior

36:54.000 --> 36:59.000
in order not to get an undesirable result.

37:00.000 --> 37:03.000
Consequently, it will be an abomination of undesirable behavior.

37:04.000 --> 37:05.000
Or a punishment.

37:06.000 --> 37:08.000
Skinner, and we will talk about this a little later,

37:09.000 --> 37:11.000
considers not only reinforcement, but also punishment.

37:12.000 --> 37:14.000
Reinforcement contributes to behavior,

37:15.000 --> 37:17.000
but punishment, on the contrary,

37:18.000 --> 37:20.000
stops any behavior.

37:21.000 --> 37:27.000
Therefore, Skinner introduces a new concept of behavior,

37:28.000 --> 37:29.000
operant behavior.

37:30.000 --> 37:34.000
Or he calls it a behavior

37:35.000 --> 37:36.000
conditioned on the type R,

37:37.000 --> 37:38.000
the type of reaction.

37:39.000 --> 37:41.000
That is, it is not important here the stimulus that affected me,

37:41.000 --> 37:44.000
but the reaction that I will get

37:45.000 --> 37:47.000
if I implement a program of any behavior.

37:48.000 --> 37:49.000
If this reaction suits me,

37:50.000 --> 37:51.000
it reinforces my behavior.

37:52.000 --> 37:53.000
If it does not suit me,

37:54.000 --> 37:57.000
it leads to an abomination of undesirable behavior.

37:58.000 --> 38:01.000
If a child goes to school

38:02.000 --> 38:04.000
and, accordingly,

38:05.000 --> 38:07.000
he is encouraged for good grades,

38:08.000 --> 38:10.000
for additional tasks that he does,

38:11.000 --> 38:12.000
he likes to study.

38:13.000 --> 38:16.000
If a child is forced to go to school,

38:17.000 --> 38:18.000
which he does not want,

38:19.000 --> 38:20.000
then, accordingly,

38:21.000 --> 38:24.000
the unfortunate 11 years that we spend in school

38:25.000 --> 38:27.000
because we do not do what we need,

38:28.000 --> 38:29.000
but we are forced to do,

38:30.000 --> 38:32.000
this is a so-called negative reinforcement,

38:33.000 --> 38:34.000
or an aversive one.

38:35.000 --> 38:36.000
And a little later we will talk about this.

38:37.000 --> 38:40.000
As for behaviorism and the learning process,

38:41.000 --> 38:44.000
Skinner not only introduced

38:45.000 --> 38:48.000
such a type of learning as operative behavior,

38:49.000 --> 38:52.000
based on the expected consequences,

38:53.000 --> 38:57.000
but also paid a lot of attention to the analysis of

38:58.000 --> 39:01.000
the existing modes of reinforcement and punishment,

39:02.000 --> 39:05.000
the existing modes of assistance

39:06.000 --> 39:08.000
in the development of one or another behavior,

39:08.000 --> 39:11.000
such as accuracy, scrupulosity,

39:12.000 --> 39:14.000
responsibility, pedanticity,

39:15.000 --> 39:19.000
accurate implementation of bureaucratic frameworks.

39:20.000 --> 39:24.000
And what are the ways that will allow us

39:25.000 --> 39:30.000
to prevent the manifestation of undesirable behavior?

39:31.000 --> 39:32.000
Delay,

39:33.000 --> 39:36.000
lack of interest in work,

39:36.000 --> 39:38.000
sitting at work,

39:39.000 --> 39:41.000
unwillingness to work,

39:42.000 --> 39:45.000
formal attitude to work, and so on.

39:46.000 --> 39:48.000
That is, all those problems that arise in any person

39:49.000 --> 39:51.000
in his daily work,

39:52.000 --> 39:55.000
because work takes up most of our life,

39:56.000 --> 39:58.000
perhaps even more than sleep.

39:59.000 --> 40:02.000
So, what types,

40:03.000 --> 40:05.000
what modes of reinforcement does Skinner give?

40:06.000 --> 40:07.000
This is very important,

40:08.000 --> 40:10.000
because Skinner was essentially an operationalist.

40:11.000 --> 40:14.000
All his work, all his achievements,

40:15.000 --> 40:17.000
they are so good that the structure of the operation

40:18.000 --> 40:20.000
that must be performed is always prescribed

40:21.000 --> 40:23.000
in order to get the desired result.

40:24.000 --> 40:27.000
Despite all the abundance of possible modes of reinforcement,

40:28.000 --> 40:30.000
you can see two main types.

40:31.000 --> 40:34.000
One type of reinforcement is related to time.

40:34.000 --> 40:38.000
After I have made a certain reaction,

40:39.000 --> 40:41.000
a certain consequence occurs,

40:42.000 --> 40:45.000
and accordingly, it is necessary to wait a certain time

40:46.000 --> 40:48.000
for this consequence to occur.

40:49.000 --> 40:50.000
If, after this time,

40:51.000 --> 40:52.000
the consequence does not occur,

40:53.000 --> 40:55.000
then the behavior is not reinforced.

40:56.000 --> 40:58.000
If, after a certain time,

40:59.000 --> 41:02.000
a certain consequence occurs,

41:02.000 --> 41:05.000
then the behavior is reinforced and fixed.

41:06.000 --> 41:09.000
This is the so-called temporary reinforcement,

41:10.000 --> 41:11.000
when the criterion is time.

41:12.000 --> 41:14.000
After a certain reaction is made,

41:15.000 --> 41:17.000
it takes some time for any event to occur.

41:18.000 --> 41:19.000
And the second type of reinforcement,

41:20.000 --> 41:22.000
the so-called proportional reinforcement,

41:23.000 --> 41:25.000
is when a certain reaction is made,

41:26.000 --> 41:31.000
and a certain number of consequences must occur after it.

41:32.000 --> 41:37.000
For example, if I do not be late for work,

41:38.000 --> 41:39.000
but I come on time,

41:40.000 --> 41:43.000
it will mean that I will be set an example to others,

41:44.000 --> 41:45.000
I will be on a good score,

41:46.000 --> 41:50.000
I will be awarded with prizes for the performance discipline,

41:51.000 --> 41:57.000
I will be given a notice for further personnel promotion,

41:58.000 --> 41:59.000
and so on.

41:59.000 --> 42:01.000
So, the reaction is one, I come on time.

42:02.000 --> 42:06.000
But there can be several consequences of this reaction.

42:07.000 --> 42:08.000
This is proportional reinforcement.

42:09.000 --> 42:10.000
Again, this is a very important point,

42:11.000 --> 42:16.000
because it is connected with the necessary amount of effort

42:17.000 --> 42:19.000
that must be applied to a person

42:20.000 --> 42:22.000
in order to achieve the desired result in an operant way,

42:23.000 --> 42:25.000
in a behavioral way.

42:26.000 --> 42:28.000
When we talk about motivation,

42:29.000 --> 42:32.000
this is a direct example.

42:33.000 --> 42:35.000
We have increased the salary.

42:36.000 --> 42:40.000
Is this enough to increase the efficiency of our employees?

42:41.000 --> 42:42.000
Or not?

42:43.000 --> 42:45.000
How much should we increase the salary?

42:46.000 --> 42:48.000
Should the whole team be increased?

42:49.000 --> 42:50.000
Should we introduce a system of fines?

42:51.000 --> 42:53.000
Should we introduce a progressive scale

42:53.000 --> 42:57.000
or a premium scale?

42:58.000 --> 43:01.000
These are numerous questions

43:02.000 --> 43:05.000
that are connected with a certain amount of reactions

43:06.000 --> 43:09.000
to the same behavioral action.

43:10.000 --> 43:14.000
Why do we spend so much time on reinforcement?

43:15.000 --> 43:16.000
All these types of reinforcement,

43:17.000 --> 43:18.000
both temporal and proportional,

43:18.000 --> 43:23.000
are directly connected with our business behavior.

43:24.000 --> 43:25.000
Behavior during negotiations,

43:26.000 --> 43:27.000
successful negotiations,

43:28.000 --> 43:30.000
behavior in communication,

43:31.000 --> 43:33.000
psychological climate in the team.

43:34.000 --> 43:36.000
All this is a behavior of a person.

43:37.000 --> 43:43.000
And depending on the reinforcement that we receive,

43:44.000 --> 43:46.000
a certain behavior is formed,

43:46.000 --> 43:49.000
certain reactions are formed,

43:50.000 --> 43:52.000
certain ways of communication are formed.

43:53.000 --> 43:54.000
People in the team,

43:55.000 --> 43:57.000
subordinates and managers,

43:58.000 --> 44:00.000
managers of the same level,

44:01.000 --> 44:03.000
that is, the horizontal and vertical levels.

44:04.000 --> 44:06.000
Of course, Skinner, as we have already said,

44:07.000 --> 44:09.000
was not limited only to reinforcements.

44:10.000 --> 44:12.000
Skinner understood perfectly

44:13.000 --> 44:16.000
that behaviorists are generally based on experience.

44:17.000 --> 44:19.000
These are people who work with common sense.

44:20.000 --> 44:23.000
Why do behaviorists have a lot of results?

44:24.000 --> 44:27.000
Behaviorists observe events,

44:28.000 --> 44:31.000
observe the facts that happen in our everyday life

44:32.000 --> 44:36.000
and try to justify these facts,

44:37.000 --> 44:39.000
to highlight from them any components

44:39.000 --> 44:42.000
that we need to improve

44:43.000 --> 44:45.000
or that we need to get rid of.

44:46.000 --> 44:47.000
If we talk about improvement,

44:48.000 --> 44:49.000
it is reinforcement.

44:50.000 --> 44:52.000
But, of course, there are a huge number of behavioral reactions

44:53.000 --> 44:54.000
that we would like to get rid of.

44:55.000 --> 44:56.000
I'm not talking about smoking,

44:57.000 --> 44:58.000
alcohol consumption,

44:59.000 --> 45:00.000
we are talking about the business environment.

45:01.000 --> 45:02.000
For example, we need to get rid of

45:03.000 --> 45:04.000
negligent attitude to work,

45:05.000 --> 45:06.000
from being late,

45:06.000 --> 45:09.000
from the rays that occur in employees,

45:10.000 --> 45:12.000
from very long lunches,

45:13.000 --> 45:14.000
from long absence at work,

45:15.000 --> 45:16.000
from frequent overdoses.

45:17.000 --> 45:18.000
Any of you will give a lot of examples

45:19.000 --> 45:20.000
of those or other poetic reactions

45:21.000 --> 45:22.000
that do not please employees.

45:23.000 --> 45:24.000
We will not consider the question

45:25.000 --> 45:27.000
whether these reactions are really bad,

45:28.000 --> 45:29.000
whether they really need to be changed.

45:30.000 --> 45:32.000
We assume that there is a leader

45:33.000 --> 45:34.000
and there are his subordinates.

45:34.000 --> 45:35.000
The leader is not satisfied with something

45:36.000 --> 45:38.000
and he wants his displeasing behavior

45:39.000 --> 45:41.000
to be changed.

45:42.000 --> 45:45.000
Skinner says that all this can be achieved

45:46.000 --> 45:48.000
by means of punishment.

45:49.000 --> 45:50.000
Speaking of punishment,

45:51.000 --> 45:53.000
Skinner uses the term

45:54.000 --> 45:56.000
of an aversive stimulus.

45:57.000 --> 45:59.000
Aversive is unpleasant, painful.

46:00.000 --> 46:02.000
If reinforcement is what we want,

46:02.000 --> 46:04.000
then aversion is what we do not want.

46:05.000 --> 46:07.000
We do not want to be stabbed,

46:08.000 --> 46:10.000
we do not want to be cold,

46:11.000 --> 46:13.000
we do not want to be deprived of bonuses,

46:14.000 --> 46:16.000
we do not want to be constantly reworked.

46:17.000 --> 46:18.000
All these aversive stimuli

46:19.000 --> 46:20.000
work on a person,

46:21.000 --> 46:23.000
they constantly function on a person.

46:24.000 --> 46:25.000
Any of us will say that

46:26.000 --> 46:28.000
there is something he wants

46:29.000 --> 46:31.000
and there is something he does not want

46:32.000 --> 46:33.000
but he has to make up with.

46:34.000 --> 46:35.000
These are aversive stimuli.

46:36.000 --> 46:39.000
As for these stimuli,

46:40.000 --> 46:42.000
Skinner proposes the idea

46:43.000 --> 46:45.000
of an aversive control

46:46.000 --> 46:48.000
