01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:07.000
that it corresponds

01:24:08.000 --> 01:24:09.000
to the changed conditions

01:24:10.000 --> 01:24:11.000
that exist.

01:24:12.000 --> 01:24:13.000
Again,

01:24:14.000 --> 01:24:15.000
it's a very simple situation.

01:24:16.000 --> 01:24:17.000
We can observe

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:19.000
how a successful manager

01:24:20.000 --> 01:24:21.000
gives instructions

01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:23.000
to other managers

01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:25.000
that are subordinate to him.

01:24:25.000 --> 01:24:26.000
How does he organize their work?

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:28.000
If we

01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:30.000
start giving instructions

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:32.000
to other managers

01:24:33.000 --> 01:24:34.000
instead of him

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:36.000
in the absence of a manager

01:24:37.000 --> 01:24:38.000
I think

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:40.000
we will get

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:42.000
a not so clear reaction

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:44.000
because our status

01:24:45.000 --> 01:24:46.000
does not correspond

01:24:47.000 --> 01:24:48.000
to our behavior.

01:24:49.000 --> 01:24:50.000
He can lead

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:52.000
because other managers

01:24:53.000 --> 01:24:54.000
are in the same position.

01:24:55.000 --> 01:24:56.000
He is authoritative.

01:24:57.000 --> 01:24:58.000
He knows

01:24:59.000 --> 01:25:00.000
what to do

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:02.000
and how to do it.

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:04.000
His status

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:06.000
corresponds to his behavior.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:08.000
Ours does not.

01:25:09.000 --> 01:25:10.000
If we just

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:12.000
reproduce

01:25:13.000 --> 01:25:14.000
a certain behavior

01:25:15.000 --> 01:25:16.000
and monkey it

01:25:17.000 --> 01:25:18.000
not because we want to

01:25:19.000 --> 01:25:20.000
but because we see

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:22.000
how a person interacts

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:24.000
with others

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:26.000
and we think

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:28.000
that if we behave

01:25:29.000 --> 01:25:30.000
we will get

01:25:31.000 --> 01:25:32.000
the same results.

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:34.000
That's right.

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:36.000
We can reproduce

01:25:37.000 --> 01:25:38.000
gestures,

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:40.000
facial expressions,

01:25:41.000 --> 01:25:42.000
even voice parodies

01:25:43.000 --> 01:25:44.000
but

01:25:45.000 --> 01:25:46.000
we have different statuses.

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:48.000
That's why

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:50.000
a mirrored motor

01:25:51.000 --> 01:25:52.000
reproductive process

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:54.000
in our performance

01:25:55.000 --> 01:25:56.000
is more valuable

01:25:57.000 --> 01:25:58.000
than the natural processes

01:25:59.000 --> 01:26:00.000
that come from

01:26:01.000 --> 01:26:02.000
a status manager.

01:26:03.000 --> 01:26:04.000
By the way,

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:06.000
it's obvious

01:26:07.000 --> 01:26:08.000
but remember

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:10.000
how often

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:12.000
you had to see

01:26:13.000 --> 01:26:14.000
such reactions

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:16.000
and how often

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:18.000
it was funny

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:20.000
because you understood

01:26:21.000 --> 01:26:22.000
why a person does it

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:24.000
and what it leads to

01:26:25.000 --> 01:26:26.000
and what it doesn't.

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:28.000
And finally

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:30.000
the fourth

01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:32.000
characteristic

01:26:33.000 --> 01:26:34.000
of the observation

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:36.000
is the motivational processes.

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:38.000
A person's motivation.

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:40.000
And here

01:26:41.000 --> 01:26:42.000
we should say

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:44.000
that Bandura

01:26:45.000 --> 01:26:46.000
in this point

01:26:47.000 --> 01:26:48.000
is far from

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:50.000
traditional behavioral approaches.

01:26:51.000 --> 01:26:52.000
Behaviorists

01:26:52.000 --> 01:26:53.000
don't consider

01:26:54.000 --> 01:26:55.000
motivational processes.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:26:57.000
Motivation is the reason

01:26:58.000 --> 01:26:59.000
for a person's behavior.

01:27:00.000 --> 01:27:01.000
So, the behaviorists

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:03.000
had a simple motivation.

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:05.000
The stimulus-reaction

01:27:06.000 --> 01:27:07.000
is the motivation

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:09.000
that makes a person

01:27:10.000 --> 01:27:11.000
do what he does.

01:27:12.000 --> 01:27:13.000
That's all.

01:27:14.000 --> 01:27:15.000
There was a clear motivation.

01:27:16.000 --> 01:27:17.000
A person

01:27:18.000 --> 01:27:19.000
was affected

01:27:20.000 --> 01:27:21.000
by external factors.

01:27:22.000 --> 01:27:23.000
I was asked to report.

01:27:24.000 --> 01:27:25.000
I had to report

01:27:26.000 --> 01:27:27.000
on my expenses

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:29.000
and I did

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:31.000
the right thing.

01:27:32.000 --> 01:27:33.000
That's the motivation.

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:35.000
Bandura

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:37.000
talks about motivation

01:27:38.000 --> 01:27:39.000
in the psychological sense of the word.

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:41.000
A person has

01:27:42.000 --> 01:27:43.000
internal variables

01:27:44.000 --> 01:27:45.000
and a person's motivation

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:47.000
is not only

01:27:48.000 --> 01:27:49.000
connected with external stimuli.

01:27:50.000 --> 01:27:51.000
Here Bandura

01:27:52.000 --> 01:27:53.000
talks about

01:27:54.000 --> 01:27:55.000
objectivity.

01:27:56.000 --> 01:27:57.000
External stimuli are active.

01:27:58.000 --> 01:27:59.000
But

01:28:00.000 --> 01:28:01.000
how I will react,

01:28:02.000 --> 01:28:03.000
what will be the real reasons

01:28:04.000 --> 01:28:05.000
for my behavior

01:28:06.000 --> 01:28:07.000
are determined by my internal

01:28:08.000 --> 01:28:09.000
cognitive map,

01:28:10.000 --> 01:28:11.000
my internal variables.

01:28:12.000 --> 01:28:13.000
That's the I

01:28:14.000 --> 01:28:15.000
in the scheme

01:28:16.000 --> 01:28:17.000
that concerns

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:19.000
the cognitive behavioral approaches.

01:28:20.000 --> 01:28:21.000
And, therefore,

01:28:22.000 --> 01:28:23.000
there is a punishment.

01:28:24.000 --> 01:28:25.000
But,

01:28:26.000 --> 01:28:27.000
and this is the main difference

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:29.000
with Skinner

01:28:30.000 --> 01:28:31.000
or radical behaviorism.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:33.000
If the punishment

01:28:34.000 --> 01:28:35.000
for Skinner

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:37.000
was the punishment

01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:39.000
and reinforcement from the outside,

01:28:40.000 --> 01:28:41.000
Bandura talks about

01:28:42.000 --> 01:28:43.000
self-reinforcement

01:28:44.000 --> 01:28:45.000
and self-punishment

01:28:46.000 --> 01:28:47.000
and self-regulation.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:28:49.000
A person

01:28:49.000 --> 01:28:50.000
is interested in

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:52.000
animals.

01:28:53.000 --> 01:28:54.000
Bandura was a behaviorist,

01:28:55.000 --> 01:28:56.000
so he didn't deal

01:28:57.000 --> 01:28:58.000
with one person.

01:28:59.000 --> 01:29:00.000
He was interested in the whole

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:02.000
psychological range.

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:04.000
A person becomes an active being

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:06.000
and the reason for his behavior

01:29:07.000 --> 01:29:08.000
is not in the outside.

01:29:09.000 --> 01:29:10.000
The outside is an external factor.

01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:12.000
It is inside a person.

01:29:13.000 --> 01:29:14.000
This was the most fundamental

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:16.000
departure from behaviorism.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:18.000
And here it is clear

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:20.000
that in the cognitive behavioral approach

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:22.000
all the cognitive

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:24.000
and motivational processes

01:29:25.000 --> 01:29:26.000
are launched.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:28.000
And now, in order to understand

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:30.000
how and why a person acts,

01:29:31.000 --> 01:29:32.000
we need to address

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:34.000
his motives,

01:29:35.000 --> 01:29:36.000
emotions,

01:29:37.000 --> 01:29:38.000
desires, needs.

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:41.000
Although, of course,

01:29:42.000 --> 01:29:43.000
Bandura in this case

01:29:44.000 --> 01:29:45.000
also does not depart from behaviorism.

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:47.000
We should address them

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:48.000
in order to reinforce

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:50.000
the desired operant behavior.

01:29:51.000 --> 01:29:52.000
I behave in order to get

01:29:53.000 --> 01:29:54.000
the desired results for me.

01:29:55.000 --> 01:29:56.000
Depending on the results

01:29:57.000 --> 01:29:58.000
I get,

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:00.000
I modify my behavior.

01:30:01.000 --> 01:30:02.000
But I do it.

01:30:03.000 --> 01:30:04.000
I, a person,

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:06.000
become active.

01:30:07.000 --> 01:30:08.000
And now

01:30:09.000 --> 01:30:10.000
the spectrum,

01:30:11.000 --> 01:30:12.000
the center of a person's behavior

01:30:13.000 --> 01:30:14.000
is transferred from the outside to the inside.

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:16.000
This was really

01:30:17.000 --> 01:30:18.000
a kind of

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:20.000
a return to behaviorism

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:22.000
of the inner world of a person.

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:24.000
This is what

01:30:25.000 --> 01:30:26.000
led to

01:30:27.000 --> 01:30:28.000
the elimination

01:30:29.000 --> 01:30:30.000
of behaviorism

01:30:31.000 --> 01:30:32.000
and to the beginning

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:34.000
of Watson's behaviorism.

01:30:36.000 --> 01:30:37.000
But Bandura, again,

01:30:38.000 --> 01:30:39.000
tries to make

01:30:40.000 --> 01:30:41.000
these motivational processes

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:43.000
tangible,

01:30:44.000 --> 01:30:45.000
visible,

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:46.000
and perceptible.

01:30:47.000 --> 01:30:48.000
At the same time,

01:30:50.000 --> 01:30:51.000
just like Skinner,

01:30:52.000 --> 01:30:53.000
he does not stop

01:30:54.000 --> 01:30:55.000
at the selection of

01:30:56.000 --> 01:30:57.000
these components

01:30:58.000 --> 01:30:59.000
and introduces

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:01.000
the concept of indirect reinforcement

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:03.000
and such an important factor

01:31:04.000 --> 01:31:05.000
as self-effectiveness.

01:31:06.000 --> 01:31:07.000
The ineffectiveness

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:09.000
of a person's behavior

01:31:10.000 --> 01:31:11.000
is a very important factor.

01:31:11.000 --> 01:31:12.000
The ineffectiveness of a person's behavior,

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:14.000
which we see from the outside,

01:31:15.000 --> 01:31:16.000
is the assessment of

01:31:17.000 --> 01:31:18.000
the effectiveness

01:31:19.000 --> 01:31:20.000
of one's own behavior.

01:31:21.000 --> 01:31:22.000
Again,

01:31:23.000 --> 01:31:24.000
no one else assesses

01:31:25.000 --> 01:31:26.000
how effective you are,

01:31:27.000 --> 01:31:28.000
which is typical for behaviorism.

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:30.000
But a person himself assesses

01:31:31.000 --> 01:31:32.000
how effective he is

01:31:33.000 --> 01:31:34.000
and how to increase

01:31:35.000 --> 01:31:36.000
his effectiveness.

01:31:37.000 --> 01:31:38.000
A person punishes himself

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:40.000
if he fails

01:31:41.000 --> 01:31:42.000
and he reinforces himself

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:44.000
if he has succeeded.

01:31:46.000 --> 01:31:47.000
As for

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:49.000
indirect reinforcement,

01:31:50.000 --> 01:31:51.000
in fact,

01:31:52.000 --> 01:31:53.000
indirect reinforcement

01:31:54.000 --> 01:31:55.000
is an observation

01:31:56.000 --> 01:31:57.000
of the behavior of the model.

01:31:58.000 --> 01:31:59.000
Let's recall Skinner's reinforcement.

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:01.000
It was necessarily external.

01:32:02.000 --> 01:32:03.000
There is an external stimulus,

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:05.000
I behave,

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:07.000
and my reinforcement

01:32:08.000 --> 01:32:09.000
is the result

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:10.000
of my achievement.

01:32:11.000 --> 01:32:12.000
If I get

01:32:13.000 --> 01:32:14.000
the desired result,

01:32:15.000 --> 01:32:16.000
it is a reinforcement

01:32:17.000 --> 01:32:18.000
of the desired behavior.

01:32:20.000 --> 01:32:21.000
Bandura has a different situation.

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:26.000
I look at the behavior of the model

01:32:27.000 --> 01:32:28.000
and I see

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:30.000
that in some situations

01:32:31.000 --> 01:32:32.000
the model is more successful

01:32:33.000 --> 01:32:34.000
than in others.

01:32:35.000 --> 01:32:36.000
Some actions

01:32:37.000 --> 01:32:38.000
of the model

01:32:39.000 --> 01:32:40.000
are more successful

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:42.000
than others.

01:32:43.000 --> 01:32:44.000
And I begin to realize

01:32:45.000 --> 01:32:47.000
from the entire model behavior

01:32:48.000 --> 01:32:50.000
these successful forms of behavior.

01:32:51.000 --> 01:32:52.000
I reinforce myself

01:32:53.000 --> 01:32:55.000
by observing the model.

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:00.000
I haven't done anything yet.

01:33:01.000 --> 01:33:02.000
I mean,

01:33:03.000 --> 01:33:04.000
I don't have a result yet

01:33:05.000 --> 01:33:06.000
with its consequences

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:08.000
in order to reinforce my behavior.

01:33:09.000 --> 01:33:10.000
I see that if the model

01:33:11.000 --> 01:33:12.000
did such and such actions,

01:33:13.000 --> 01:33:14.000
it got the desired result

01:33:15.000 --> 01:33:16.000
with the desired consequences.

01:33:17.000 --> 01:33:18.000
I begin to reinforce

01:33:19.000 --> 01:33:20.000
not by my behavior,

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:22.000
but only by observing

01:33:23.000 --> 01:33:24.000
the behavior of the model.

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:26.000
This is indirect reinforcement.

01:33:27.000 --> 01:33:28.000
Not directly, but indirectly.

01:33:29.000 --> 01:33:30.000
This is not my behavior,

01:33:31.000 --> 01:33:32.000
this is the behavior of the model,

01:33:33.000 --> 01:33:34.000
and I only observe its success.

01:33:35.000 --> 01:33:36.000
And then I try to reproduce it.

01:33:37.000 --> 01:33:38.000
I don't know yet if I will succeed.

01:33:39.000 --> 01:33:40.000
I can copy the model

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:42.000
one by one

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:44.000
with the suit, glasses,

01:33:45.000 --> 01:33:46.000
hairstyle, and so on,

01:33:47.000 --> 01:33:48.000
and remain unsuccessful.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:51.000
But this indirect reinforcement

01:33:52.000 --> 01:33:53.000
will later require

01:33:54.000 --> 01:33:55.000
real reinforcement

01:33:56.000 --> 01:33:57.000
from my results.

01:33:58.000 --> 01:33:59.000
But first, these are the results

01:34:00.000 --> 01:34:01.000
that I see in the model.

01:34:02.000 --> 01:34:03.000
And then

01:34:04.000 --> 01:34:05.000
my successes

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:07.000
will be reflected

01:34:07.000 --> 01:34:08.000
from the point of view

01:34:09.000 --> 01:34:10.000
of my own assessment

01:34:11.000 --> 01:34:12.000
of the effectiveness

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:14.000
of my behavior.

01:34:15.000 --> 01:34:16.000
I do not assess my experiences.

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:18.000
This is not present

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:20.000
in the cognitive behavioral approach.

01:34:21.000 --> 01:34:22.000
I, again, assess the result

01:34:23.000 --> 01:34:24.000
of my behavior.

01:34:25.000 --> 01:34:26.000
But I do it myself

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:28.000
by the reinforcement,

01:34:29.000 --> 01:34:30.000
as we talked about.

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:32.000
Moreover, again,

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:34.000
the reinforcement highlights

01:34:35.000 --> 01:34:36.000
four fundamental elements

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:38.000
that allow

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:40.000
to increase

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:42.000
the effectiveness of a person,

01:34:43.000 --> 01:34:44.000
that is, to increase

01:34:45.000 --> 01:34:46.000
his own opinion

01:34:47.000 --> 01:34:48.000
about himself.

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:50.000
This has not yet been in behaviorism.

01:34:51.000 --> 01:34:52.000
A person begins

01:34:53.000 --> 01:34:54.000
to assess himself.

01:34:55.000 --> 01:34:56.000
And from the point of view of Bandura,

01:34:57.000 --> 01:34:58.000
a person can assess himself

01:34:59.000 --> 01:35:00.000
objectively,

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:02.000
not passionately,

01:35:03.000 --> 01:35:04.000
we all know that we are the best,

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:06.000
but objectively,

01:35:07.000 --> 01:35:08.000
we are the worst.

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:10.000
If he really will come from

01:35:11.000 --> 01:35:12.000
four criteria,

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:14.000
which Bandura highlighted.

01:35:15.000 --> 01:35:16.000
The first criterion is

01:35:17.000 --> 01:35:18.000
the ability of a person

01:35:19.000 --> 01:35:20.000
to build

01:35:21.000 --> 01:35:22.000
observable behavior.

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:24.000
There is a model,

01:35:25.000 --> 01:35:26.000
I highlighted it with attention,

01:35:27.000 --> 01:35:28.000
I kept its behavior in my memory,

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:30.000
but now I need

01:35:31.000 --> 01:35:32.000
to reproduce this work.

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:34.000
Everyone gets it in different ways.

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:36.000
Someone

01:35:37.000 --> 01:35:38.000
parodies Pugachev,

01:35:39.000 --> 01:35:40.000
Kabzon,

01:35:41.000 --> 01:35:42.000
but nevertheless he does not become

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:44.000
Pugachev or Kabzon,

01:35:45.000 --> 01:35:46.000
he becomes a parodist.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:48.000
In this regard,

01:35:49.000 --> 01:35:50.000
again, how effective behavior

01:35:51.000 --> 01:35:52.000
I will build

01:35:53.000 --> 01:35:54.000
to be not a parodist,

01:35:55.000 --> 01:35:56.000
but a specialist,

01:35:57.000 --> 01:35:58.000
who will be appreciated

01:35:59.000 --> 01:36:00.000
no less than the model

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:02.000
I am focused on.

01:36:03.000 --> 01:36:04.000
The second criterion

01:36:05.000 --> 01:36:06.000
of the most effective

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:08.000
is the presence of

01:36:09.000 --> 01:36:10.000
indirect experience.

01:36:11.000 --> 01:36:12.000
Not indirect reinforcement,

01:36:13.000 --> 01:36:14.000
but indirect experience.

01:36:15.000 --> 01:36:16.000
Indirect experience is

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:18.000
not directly related

01:36:19.000 --> 01:36:20.000
to my behavior,

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:22.000
but it is a

01:36:23.000 --> 01:36:24.000
coexisting experience.

01:36:25.000 --> 01:36:26.000
There is a basic experience

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:28.000
that I get by doing

01:36:29.000 --> 01:36:30.000
these or those actions.

01:36:31.000 --> 01:36:32.000
And here I get the result.

01:36:33.000 --> 01:36:34.000
But in addition to this result,

01:36:35.000 --> 01:36:36.000
I get respect

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:38.000
and respect.

01:36:39.000 --> 01:36:40.000
I get

01:36:41.000 --> 01:36:42.000
those or those labels

01:36:43.000 --> 01:36:44.000
conflict,

01:36:45.000 --> 01:36:46.000
non-conflict,

01:36:47.000 --> 01:36:48.000
cooperative,

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:50.000
competitive.

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:52.000
That is,

01:36:53.000 --> 01:36:54.000
every result,

01:36:55.000 --> 01:36:56.000
in addition to the desired consequences,

01:36:57.000 --> 01:36:58.000
has another consequence.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:00.000
And these consequences

01:37:01.000 --> 01:37:02.000
are also very important

01:37:03.000 --> 01:37:04.000
for assessing me

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:06.000
as an effective specialist,

01:37:07.000 --> 01:37:08.000
for being able to pay attention,

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:10.000
to be able to notice

01:37:11.000 --> 01:37:12.000
not only the results of behavior,

01:37:13.000 --> 01:37:14.000
but also the results

01:37:15.000 --> 01:37:16.000
that are associated with it.

01:37:17.000 --> 01:37:18.000
The third criterion

01:37:19.000 --> 01:37:20.000
of the most effective

01:37:21.000 --> 01:37:22.000
is verbal offense.

01:37:23.000 --> 01:37:24.000
This concerns

01:37:25.000 --> 01:37:26.000
only a person.

01:37:27.000 --> 01:37:28.000
Only,

01:37:29.000 --> 01:37:30.000
in any case,

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:32.000
as we know now,

01:37:33.000 --> 01:37:34.000
we will not go into different

01:37:35.000 --> 01:37:36.000
esoteric experiences

01:37:37.000 --> 01:37:38.000
of language

01:37:39.000 --> 01:37:40.000
possession.

01:37:41.000 --> 01:37:42.000
This is only a person.

01:37:43.000 --> 01:37:44.000
And, accordingly,

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:46.000
if we are talking about a person,

01:37:47.000 --> 01:37:48.000
then

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:50.000
I can

01:37:51.000 --> 01:37:52.000
verbally,

01:37:53.000 --> 01:37:54.000
cognitively,

01:37:55.000 --> 01:37:56.000
make up one or another

01:37:57.000 --> 01:37:58.000
idea about my actions,

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:00.000
give myself an assessment,

01:38:01.000 --> 01:38:02.000
express the level of my effectiveness

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:04.000
in words.

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:06.000
Again, this is a very significant

01:38:07.000 --> 01:38:08.000
criterion of the most effective

01:38:09.000 --> 01:38:10.000
is verbal offense.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:12.000
Because before this,

01:38:13.000 --> 01:38:14.000
people did not pay attention

01:38:15.000 --> 01:38:16.000
to speech at all.

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:18.000
Speech for them was just

01:38:19.000 --> 01:38:20.000
a thought spread out in the ear.

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:22.000
Purely a bichloral approach.

01:38:23.000 --> 01:38:24.000
We think,

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:26.000
we want to convey our thoughts

01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:28.000
to another person.

01:38:29.000 --> 01:38:30.000
And speech is just

01:38:31.000 --> 01:38:32.000
an articulation of our thoughts.

01:38:33.000 --> 01:38:34.000
The situation with Bandura

01:38:35.000 --> 01:38:36.000
changes fundamentally.

01:38:37.000 --> 01:38:38.000
The fact that I am a professional,

01:38:39.000 --> 01:38:40.000
that my achievements

01:38:41.000 --> 01:38:42.000
are worthy of being

01:38:43.000 --> 01:38:44.000
reproduced,

01:38:45.000 --> 01:38:46.000
worthy of self-respect,

01:38:47.000 --> 01:38:48.000
in fact,

01:38:49.000 --> 01:38:50.000
this is a self-assessment

01:38:51.000 --> 01:38:52.000
given to a person.

01:38:53.000 --> 01:38:54.000
Am I successful in life?

01:38:55.000 --> 01:38:56.000
Am I unsuccessful?

01:38:57.000 --> 01:38:58.000
Am I successful

01:38:59.000 --> 01:39:00.000
in perceiving the behavior of a model?

01:39:01.000 --> 01:39:02.000
Whether I am modeling a model,

01:39:03.000 --> 01:39:04.000
will I become

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:06.000
the same person

01:39:07.000 --> 01:39:08.000
for someone else

01:39:09.000 --> 01:39:10.000
as I am modeling

01:39:11.000 --> 01:39:12.000
for myself today?

01:39:13.000 --> 01:39:14.000
This is a verbal offense.

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:16.000
These are the cognitive and

01:39:17.000 --> 01:39:18.000
thought structures

01:39:19.000 --> 01:39:20.000
that are characteristic of a person.

01:39:21.000 --> 01:39:22.000
And the fourth criterion,

01:39:23.000 --> 01:39:24.000
again,

01:39:25.000 --> 01:39:26.000
is not characteristic of bichlorism,

01:39:27.000 --> 01:39:28.000
but is inherent in Bandura.

01:39:29.000 --> 01:39:30.000
This is an emotional reinforcement.

01:39:31.000 --> 01:39:32.000
No one has ever talked about

01:39:33.000 --> 01:39:34.000
emotions before Bandura

01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:36.000
in bichlorists.

01:39:37.000 --> 01:39:38.000
It is obvious that

01:39:39.000 --> 01:39:40.000
if a person is on an emotional rise,

01:39:41.000 --> 01:39:42.000
if he is happy,

01:39:43.000 --> 01:39:44.000
he is very happy.

01:39:45.000 --> 01:39:46.000
If he achieves great results

01:39:47.000 --> 01:39:48.000
where he would not have achieved them

01:39:49.000 --> 01:39:50.000
in ordinary words,

01:39:51.000 --> 01:39:52.000
if he is depressed,

01:39:53.000 --> 01:39:54.000
if he is upset,

01:39:55.000 --> 01:39:56.000
if something is wrong with him,

01:39:57.000 --> 01:39:58.000
then those actions,

01:39:59.000 --> 01:40:00.000
those reactions

01:40:01.000 --> 01:40:02.000
that were not difficult for him

01:40:03.000 --> 01:40:04.000
to do yesterday,

01:40:05.000 --> 01:40:06.000
what he did on the machine,

01:40:07.000 --> 01:40:08.000
he does not want to do it.

01:40:09.000 --> 01:40:10.000
It is because

01:40:11.000 --> 01:40:12.000
he is not in the mood.

01:40:13.000 --> 01:40:14.000
A person is a living creature.

01:40:15.000 --> 01:40:17.000
For us, this is a natural statement.

01:40:18.000 --> 01:40:19.000
But for bichlorists

01:40:20.000 --> 01:40:22.000
this statement was shocking.

01:40:23.000 --> 01:40:24.000
It was emotions

01:40:25.000 --> 01:40:26.000
that Otsun was avoiding

01:40:27.000 --> 01:40:28.000
when creating bichlorism.

01:40:29.000 --> 01:40:30.000
It was emotions that Bandura came to.

01:40:31.000 --> 01:40:32.000
When creating a cognitive-bichlorian approach,

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:34.000
he realized

01:40:35.000 --> 01:40:36.000
that if we want

01:40:37.000 --> 01:40:38.000
to build a model of human behavior,

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:40.000
we cannot take away

01:40:41.000 --> 01:40:43.000
from a person his subjectivity.

01:40:44.000 --> 01:40:46.000
These are the four criteria

01:40:47.000 --> 01:40:49.000
with which Bandura

01:40:50.000 --> 01:40:51.000
believed

01:40:52.000 --> 01:40:53.000
that a person

01:40:54.000 --> 01:40:55.000
is able to objectively

01:40:56.000 --> 01:40:58.000
assess his self-effectiveness.

01:40:59.000 --> 01:41:00.000
So,

01:41:01.000 --> 01:41:02.000
we have considered

01:41:03.000 --> 01:41:05.000
the approach to the bichlorists' training.

01:41:05.000 --> 01:41:06.000
We have looked at the changes

01:41:07.000 --> 01:41:08.000
that were made to the bichlorian theory

01:41:09.000 --> 01:41:10.000
by Bandura.

01:41:11.000 --> 01:41:12.000
But let's pay attention

01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:14.000
to the following fact.

01:41:15.000 --> 01:41:17.000
What is the principle similarity

01:41:18.000 --> 01:41:19.000
between Skinner

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:21.000
and Bandura,

01:41:22.000 --> 01:41:23.000
the approach that is fundamentally different

01:41:24.000 --> 01:41:25.000
from Skinner's approach?

01:41:26.000 --> 01:41:27.000
Both of them

01:41:28.000 --> 01:41:29.000
consider a person

01:41:30.000 --> 01:41:31.000
as a person.

01:41:32.000 --> 01:41:33.000
A person is one.

01:41:33.000 --> 01:41:34.000
A person behaves in a certain way,

01:41:35.000 --> 01:41:36.000
interacts with a person.

01:41:37.000 --> 01:41:38.000
At the same time,

01:41:39.000 --> 01:41:40.000
if Skinner's behavior

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:42.000
is related to

01:41:43.000 --> 01:41:44.000
external activity

01:41:45.000 --> 01:41:46.000
on a person,

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:48.000
Bandura

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:50.000
transfers the center of consideration

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:52.000
inside a person,

01:41:53.000 --> 01:41:54.000
and external activity

01:41:55.000 --> 01:41:56.000
moves from a person

01:41:57.000 --> 01:41:58.000
to outside.

01:41:59.000 --> 01:42:00.000
External activity can affect a person,

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:02.000
but the main thing is

01:42:03.000 --> 01:42:04.000
that if a person is affected

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:06.000
by external activity,

01:42:07.000 --> 01:42:08.000
then another obvious fact

01:42:09.000 --> 01:42:10.000
related to human behavior

01:42:11.000 --> 01:42:12.000
is left out.

01:42:13.000 --> 01:42:14.000
The fact,

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:16.000
again,

01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:18.000
in line with common sense,

01:42:19.000 --> 01:42:20.000
is that a person

01:42:21.000 --> 01:42:22.000
is a fundamentally social creature.

01:42:23.000 --> 01:42:24.000
That is,

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:26.000
a person lives among other people,

01:42:27.000 --> 01:42:28.000
and other people assess

01:42:29.000 --> 01:42:30.000
a person's behavior.

01:42:31.000 --> 01:42:32.000
A person strives to do something

01:42:33.000 --> 01:42:34.000
in order to achieve

01:42:35.000 --> 01:42:36.000
a certain place

01:42:37.000 --> 01:42:38.000
in the social hierarchy

01:42:39.000 --> 01:42:40.000
that has been created.

01:42:41.000 --> 01:42:42.000
Any behavior of a person

01:42:43.000 --> 01:42:44.000
is oriented to the reaction of other people.

01:42:45.000 --> 01:42:46.000
A person is a fundamentally social creature.

01:42:47.000 --> 01:42:48.000
Again, the idea of Aristotle,

01:42:49.000 --> 01:42:50.000
and Aristotle also said

01:42:51.000 --> 01:42:52.000
that a person is a social animal.

01:42:53.000 --> 01:42:54.000
But,

01:42:55.000 --> 01:42:56.000
it seems that

01:42:57.000 --> 01:42:58.000
such a fact

01:42:59.000 --> 01:43:00.000
has not yet been included

01:43:01.000 --> 01:43:02.000
in the behaviorist's consideration.

01:43:03.000 --> 01:43:04.000
And, in principle,

01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:06.000
it was not important

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:08.000
for the behaviorists

01:43:09.000 --> 01:43:10.000
of Skinner's logic.

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:12.000
Other people

01:43:13.000 --> 01:43:14.000
were concerned with external social factors

01:43:15.000 --> 01:43:16.000
that affect a person.

01:43:17.000 --> 01:43:18.000
This is one of the external factors,

01:43:19.000 --> 01:43:20.000
and there was no need

01:43:21.000 --> 01:43:22.000
to separate them for some reason.

01:43:23.000 --> 01:43:24.000
Bandura

01:43:25.000 --> 01:43:26.000
approached the need

01:43:27.000 --> 01:43:28.000
to take into account other people

01:43:29.000 --> 01:43:30.000
almost directly.

01:43:31.000 --> 01:43:32.000
But in this regard,

01:43:33.000 --> 01:43:34.000
he did not take into account

01:43:35.000 --> 01:43:36.000
the social behavior of a person.

01:43:37.000 --> 01:43:38.000
Although, of course,

01:43:39.000 --> 01:43:40.000
he made a lot of effort

01:43:41.000 --> 01:43:42.000
to analyze the social behavior of a person,

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:44.000
but it was not the main thing for him.

01:43:45.000 --> 01:43:46.000
As for

01:43:47.000 --> 01:43:48.000
the inclusion

01:43:49.000 --> 01:43:50.000
of the cognitive-behavioral approach

01:43:51.000 --> 01:43:52.000
of the socium,

01:43:53.000 --> 01:43:54.000
it is the merit

01:43:55.000 --> 01:43:56.000
that is associated

01:43:57.000 --> 01:43:58.000
with another significant figure

01:43:59.000 --> 01:44:00.000
of the approach,

01:44:01.000 --> 01:44:02.000
Julian Rotter.

01:44:03.000 --> 01:44:04.000
Of course,

01:44:05.000 --> 01:44:06.000
he was a supporter

01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:08.000
of the idea of Bandura's approach.

01:44:09.000 --> 01:44:10.000
They live in the same time.

01:44:11.000 --> 01:44:12.000
But Rotter

01:44:13.000 --> 01:44:14.000
focused his main attention

01:44:15.000 --> 01:44:16.000
on the fact

01:44:17.000 --> 01:44:18.000
of the social behavior

01:44:19.000 --> 01:44:20.000
of a person

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:22.000
as a cognitive-behavioral creature.

01:44:23.000 --> 01:44:24.000
At the same time,

01:44:25.000 --> 01:44:26.000
Rotter

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:28.000
is the creator

01:44:29.000 --> 01:44:30.000
of the theory of social learning.

01:44:31.000 --> 01:44:32.000
As for

01:44:33.000 --> 01:44:34.000
this theory,

01:44:35.000 --> 01:44:36.000
it is again

01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:38.000
a theory

01:44:39.000 --> 01:44:40.000
that is in line

01:44:41.000 --> 01:44:42.000
with the behavioral approach.

01:44:43.000 --> 01:44:44.000
This theory reflects

01:44:45.000 --> 01:44:46.000
the fact of the social behavior of a person

01:44:47.000 --> 01:44:48.000
and, again,

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:50.000
it solves the operational task.

01:44:51.000 --> 01:44:52.000
As for Rotter,

01:44:53.000 --> 01:44:54.000
he states that

01:44:55.000 --> 01:44:56.000
the meaning of the study

01:44:57.000 --> 01:44:58.000
of human behavior

01:44:59.000 --> 01:45:00.000
is that

01:45:01.000 --> 01:45:02.000
we could make a forecast.

01:45:03.000 --> 01:45:04.000
This is, again,

01:45:05.000 --> 01:45:06.000
the basic idea of behaviorism.

01:45:07.000 --> 01:45:08.000
We study people,

01:45:09.000 --> 01:45:10.000
we study animals

01:45:11.000 --> 01:45:12.000
in order to be able to predict

01:45:13.000 --> 01:45:14.000
how they will behave.

01:45:16.000 --> 01:45:17.000
In fact,

01:45:18.000 --> 01:45:19.000
Bandura asks a second question.

01:45:20.000 --> 01:45:21.000
In addition to the question

01:45:22.000 --> 01:45:23.000
of how to behave,

01:45:24.000 --> 01:45:25.000
Bandura asks a question

01:45:26.000 --> 01:45:27.000
of why people behave like this.

01:45:28.000 --> 01:45:29.000
And he starts to answer this question.

01:45:30.000 --> 01:45:31.000
Rotter continues to look for the answer

01:45:31.000 --> 01:45:32.000
to the question of why people behave like this.

01:45:33.000 --> 01:45:34.000
And he says that

01:45:35.000 --> 01:45:36.000
in addition to learning,

01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:38.000
modeling,

01:45:39.000 --> 01:45:40.000
observing,

01:45:41.000 --> 01:45:42.000
which Bandura mentioned,

01:45:43.000 --> 01:45:44.000
which is already social in itself,

01:45:45.000 --> 01:45:46.000
the main fact is that

01:45:47.000 --> 01:45:48.000
a person in his everyday behavior

01:45:49.000 --> 01:45:50.000
is guided by other people.

01:45:51.000 --> 01:45:52.000
Therefore,

01:45:53.000 --> 01:45:54.000
our task,

01:45:55.000 --> 01:45:56.000
the task of the cognitive behavioral approach

01:45:57.000 --> 01:45:58.000
is to build a forecast of a person's behavior.

01:45:59.000 --> 01:46:00.000
A forecast of a person's behavior

01:46:01.000 --> 01:46:02.000
is the task of analyzing

01:46:03.000 --> 01:46:04.000
the forecast of human behavior

01:46:05.000 --> 01:46:06.000
in our everyday life.

01:46:07.000 --> 01:46:08.000
But here it should be borne in mind

01:46:09.000 --> 01:46:10.000
that even with regard to behaviorists,

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:12.000
they were very careful with words.

01:46:13.000 --> 01:46:14.000
Our everyday life is a blurry concept.

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:16.000
Therefore, Rotter introduces the term

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:18.000
complex situation,

01:46:19.000 --> 01:46:20.000
the forecast of human social behavior

01:46:21.000 --> 01:46:22.000
in complex situations.

01:46:23.000 --> 01:46:24.000
In complex situations,

01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:26.000
from the point of view of multi-stimulant.

01:46:27.000 --> 01:46:28.000
There are a lot of stimuli here.

01:46:28.000 --> 01:46:29.000
First, stimuli of the external world,

01:46:30.000 --> 01:46:31.000
and secondly,

01:46:32.000 --> 01:46:33.000
which is much more complicated,

01:46:34.000 --> 01:46:35.000
these are internal stimuli,

01:46:36.000 --> 01:46:37.000
internal variables,

01:46:38.000 --> 01:46:39.000
internal cognitive maps.

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:41.000
Again,

01:46:42.000 --> 01:46:43.000
as for Rotter,

01:46:44.000 --> 01:46:45.000
he does not stop at this idea.

01:46:46.000 --> 01:46:47.000
He gives a way to solve it.

01:46:48.000 --> 01:46:49.000
How can we objectively,

01:46:50.000 --> 01:46:51.000
and this is still

01:46:52.000 --> 01:46:53.000
a behavioral methodology.

01:46:54.000 --> 01:46:55.000
And here the main thing is

01:46:56.000 --> 01:46:57.000
that we need to understand

01:46:58.000 --> 01:46:59.000
and measure,

01:47:00.000 --> 01:47:01.000
we need to analyze,

01:47:02.000 --> 01:47:03.000
we need to calculate.

01:47:04.000 --> 01:47:05.000
So, the question is,

01:47:06.000 --> 01:47:07.000
how can we measure

01:47:08.000 --> 01:47:09.000
a complex social situation?

01:47:10.000 --> 01:47:11.000
Rotter,

01:47:12.000 --> 01:47:13.000
as well as Bandura,

01:47:14.000 --> 01:47:15.000
when talking about self-effectiveness,

01:47:16.000 --> 01:47:17.000
also highlights

01:47:18.000 --> 01:47:19.000
four main variables.

01:47:20.000 --> 01:47:21.000
Behaviorists have always been looking for

01:47:22.000 --> 01:47:23.000
those variables that can be measured.

01:47:24.000 --> 01:47:25.000
Because if I want to get

01:47:26.000 --> 01:47:27.000
an objective result,

01:47:28.000 --> 01:47:29.000
I need to measure it.

01:47:30.000 --> 01:47:31.000
This is a complete analogue of natural consciousness.

01:47:32.000 --> 01:47:33.000
Rotter highlights four variables

01:47:34.000 --> 01:47:37.000
that need to be measured and studied

01:47:38.000 --> 01:47:40.000
in order to solve the basic task

01:47:41.000 --> 01:47:42.000
of building a forecast of human behavior

01:47:43.000 --> 01:47:44.000
in complex situations.

01:47:45.000 --> 01:47:50.000
And as for all the variables of Rotter,

01:47:51.000 --> 01:47:52.000
these variables

01:47:53.000 --> 01:47:54.000
are already going completely

01:47:55.000 --> 01:47:56.000
in line with behaviorism.

01:47:56.000 --> 01:47:57.000
Well, after Bandura,

01:47:58.000 --> 01:47:59.000
it was partly

01:48:00.000 --> 01:48:01.000
done simply,

01:48:02.000 --> 01:48:03.000
because Bandura was the first

01:48:04.000 --> 01:48:05.000
to make this subjective path.

01:48:06.000 --> 01:48:07.000
Rotter believes

01:48:08.000 --> 01:48:09.000
that in order to analyze

01:48:10.000 --> 01:48:11.000
human behavior,

01:48:12.000 --> 01:48:13.000
we need to know

01:48:14.000 --> 01:48:15.000
the potential of its behavior.

01:48:16.000 --> 01:48:17.000
Look,

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:19.000
potential is

01:48:20.000 --> 01:48:21.000
those possible reasons,

01:48:22.000 --> 01:48:23.000
those possible reasons

01:48:23.000 --> 01:48:24.000
and those possible results,

01:48:25.000 --> 01:48:26.000
those possible desires

01:48:27.000 --> 01:48:28.000
that a person wants to achieve.

01:48:29.000 --> 01:48:30.000
I behave,

01:48:31.000 --> 01:48:32.000
I do something,

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:34.000
I act in a certain way

01:48:35.000 --> 01:48:36.000
in order to achieve some result.

01:48:37.000 --> 01:48:38.000
I have some faith in possibilities.

01:48:39.000 --> 01:48:40.000
I can get one result,

01:48:41.000 --> 01:48:42.000
I can get many results,

01:48:43.000 --> 01:48:44.000
I can limit myself

01:48:45.000 --> 01:48:46.000
to a small number of results.

01:48:47.000 --> 01:48:48.000
Again,

01:48:49.000 --> 01:48:50.000
the same question arises here.

01:48:50.000 --> 01:48:51.000
What level of achievement,

01:48:52.000 --> 01:48:53.000
what level of commitment

01:48:54.000 --> 01:48:55.000
do I put in order to know

01:48:56.000 --> 01:48:57.000
how to compare

01:48:58.000 --> 01:48:59.000
those real achievements

01:49:00.000 --> 01:49:01.000
that I have.

01:49:02.000 --> 01:49:03.000
But,

01:49:04.000 --> 01:49:05.000
since we are talking about

01:49:06.000 --> 01:49:07.000
the potential of behavior,

01:49:08.000 --> 01:49:09.000
Rotter introduces

01:49:10.000 --> 01:49:11.000
the following criteria,

01:49:12.000 --> 01:49:13.000
the following variable,

01:49:14.000 --> 01:49:15.000
expectation.

01:49:16.000 --> 01:49:17.000
I can set

01:49:18.000 --> 01:49:19.000
a very high expectation

01:49:20.000 --> 01:49:21.000
for my behavior.

01:49:22.000 --> 01:49:23.000
And thus,

01:49:24.000 --> 01:49:25.000
in fact,

01:49:26.000 --> 01:49:27.000
I set my expectations,

01:49:28.000 --> 01:49:29.000
the prospects

01:49:30.000 --> 01:49:31.000
that I want to achieve,

01:49:32.000 --> 01:49:33.000
the data that I want to get.

01:49:34.000 --> 01:49:35.000
I build a certain goal,

01:49:36.000 --> 01:49:37.000
a certain vision,

01:49:38.000 --> 01:49:39.000
a certain belief.

01:49:40.000 --> 01:49:41.000
I set a goal for my activity

01:49:42.000 --> 01:49:43.000
for which

01:49:44.000 --> 01:49:45.000
these are my internal variables

01:49:46.000 --> 01:49:47.000
that are influenced

01:49:48.000 --> 01:49:49.000
by external stimuli

01:49:50.000 --> 01:49:51.000
that shape my behavior.

01:49:52.000 --> 01:49:53.000
Expectations

01:49:54.000 --> 01:49:55.000
determine where I am going,

01:49:56.000 --> 01:49:57.000
what I am striving for,

01:49:58.000 --> 01:49:59.000
what I want to achieve.

01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:01.000
The next variable

01:50:02.000 --> 01:50:03.000
that Rotter introduces

01:50:04.000 --> 01:50:05.000
is the value of reinforcement.

01:50:06.000 --> 01:50:07.000
Look,

01:50:08.000 --> 01:50:09.000
Skinner

01:50:10.000 --> 01:50:11.000
and Bandura

01:50:12.000 --> 01:50:13.000
all talked about reinforcement

01:50:14.000 --> 01:50:15.000
in different aspects.

01:50:16.000 --> 01:50:17.000
But Rotter makes reinforcement

01:50:18.000 --> 01:50:19.000
clearly subjective.

01:50:20.000 --> 01:50:21.000
He does not specify

01:50:22.000 --> 01:50:23.000
the value of reinforcement.

01:50:24.000 --> 01:50:25.000
Why is one

01:50:26.000 --> 01:50:27.000
or another reinforcement

01:50:28.000 --> 01:50:29.000
valuable to a person?

01:50:30.000 --> 01:50:31.000
Let's take a manager.

01:50:32.000 --> 01:50:33.000
For someone,

01:50:34.000 --> 01:50:35.000
material compensation

01:50:36.000 --> 01:50:37.000
is the only value.

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:39.000
Accordingly,

01:50:40.000 --> 01:50:41.000
everything I do is done

01:50:42.000 --> 01:50:43.000
to increase my income.

01:50:44.000 --> 01:50:45.000
For someone,

01:50:46.000 --> 01:50:47.000
the value is

01:50:48.000 --> 01:50:49.000
acquiring new knowledge,

01:50:50.000 --> 01:50:51.000
gaining experience,

01:50:52.000 --> 01:50:53.000
and professional growth.

01:50:54.000 --> 01:50:55.000
Salary is important,

01:50:56.000 --> 01:50:57.000
but the main thing for me

01:50:58.000 --> 01:50:59.000
is getting to know a new field,

01:51:00.000 --> 01:51:01.000
the opportunity to gain new experience,

01:51:02.000 --> 01:51:03.000
the opportunity to gain professional growth,

01:51:04.000 --> 01:51:05.000
which will later

01:51:06.000 --> 01:51:07.000
be reflected in salary,

01:51:08.000 --> 01:51:09.000
but not in salary.

01:51:10.000 --> 01:51:11.000
The main thing is

01:51:12.000 --> 01:51:13.000
my career and professional development.

01:51:14.000 --> 01:51:15.000
Depending on the value

01:51:16.000 --> 01:51:17.000
that we give to reinforcement,

01:51:17.000 --> 01:51:18.000
there are different priorities.

01:51:19.000 --> 01:51:20.000
Reinforcement is a choice of priorities.

01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:22.000
What do we want to get earlier,

01:51:23.000 --> 01:51:24.000
what do we allow to get later,

01:51:25.000 --> 01:51:26.000
what do we not want to get at all.

01:51:27.000 --> 01:51:28.000
Punishment.

01:51:29.000 --> 01:51:30.000
In this regard,

01:51:31.000 --> 01:51:32.000
Rotter, again,

01:51:33.000 --> 01:51:34.000
makes a person even more subjective.

01:51:35.000 --> 01:51:36.000
In this case,

01:51:37.000 --> 01:51:38.000
the value of reinforcement

01:51:39.000 --> 01:51:40.000
is determined not by external data,

01:51:41.000 --> 01:51:42.000
but by the value of each person.

01:51:43.000 --> 01:51:44.000
Then this value

01:51:45.000 --> 01:51:46.000
will be determined

01:51:47.000 --> 01:51:48.000
by social values.

01:51:49.000 --> 01:51:50.000
And, again,

01:51:51.000 --> 01:51:52.000
a social interaction will arise.

01:51:53.000 --> 01:51:54.000
There are my values,

01:51:55.000 --> 01:51:56.000
my internal variables.

01:51:57.000 --> 01:51:58.000
As for potential, expectations,

01:51:59.000 --> 01:52:00.000
values, psychology,

01:52:01.000 --> 01:52:02.000
psychological situation

01:52:03.000 --> 01:52:04.000
that will be the next variable,

01:52:05.000 --> 01:52:06.000
this is a list of internal variables.

01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:08.000
What does Rotter do?

01:52:09.000 --> 01:52:10.000
Rotter tries to operationalize

01:52:11.000 --> 01:52:12.000
this most inescapable,

01:52:13.000 --> 01:52:14.000
immeasurable internal variable,

01:52:14.000 --> 01:52:15.000
cognitive map.

01:52:16.000 --> 01:52:17.000
This value will be related

01:52:18.000 --> 01:52:19.000
to my internal values.

01:52:20.000 --> 01:52:21.000
And it is related to external values.

01:52:22.000 --> 01:52:23.000
S.

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:25.000
Accordingly,

01:52:26.000 --> 01:52:27.000
depending on this ratio,

01:52:28.000 --> 01:52:29.000
there will be different reactions.

01:52:30.000 --> 01:52:31.000
This is the original formula.

01:52:32.000 --> 01:52:33.000
Stimulus, internal variable, reaction.

01:52:34.000 --> 01:52:35.000
Here it is,

01:52:36.000 --> 01:52:37.000
the closure that arises here.

01:52:38.000 --> 01:52:39.000
And the fourth variable

01:52:40.000 --> 01:52:41.000
is psychological reaction.

01:52:41.000 --> 01:52:42.000
There is a nuance

01:52:43.000 --> 01:52:44.000
in understanding the psychological situation

01:52:45.000 --> 01:52:46.000
for Rotter.

01:52:47.000 --> 01:52:48.000
Let's not forget

01:52:49.000 --> 01:52:50.000
that Rotter is a stanobichiarist.

01:52:51.000 --> 01:52:52.000
And, accordingly,

01:52:53.000 --> 01:52:54.000
a stanobichiarist

01:52:55.000 --> 01:52:56.000
in the sense that

01:52:57.000 --> 01:52:58.000
he requires objectivity.

01:52:59.000 --> 01:53:00.000
I will not build a hypothesis,

01:53:01.000 --> 01:53:02.000
as, for example,

01:53:03.000 --> 01:53:04.000
domestic psychologists

01:53:05.000 --> 01:53:06.000
from the point of view of the operational approach,

01:53:07.000 --> 01:53:08.000
where there are only theories

01:53:09.000 --> 01:53:10.000
and no real results.

01:53:11.000 --> 01:53:12.000
I will not build a hypothesis.

01:53:13.000 --> 01:53:14.000
But

01:53:15.000 --> 01:53:16.000
every person

01:53:17.000 --> 01:53:18.000
has his own motives.

01:53:19.000 --> 01:53:20.000
Let's recall Bandura.

01:53:21.000 --> 01:53:22.000
Every person has his own desires,

01:53:23.000 --> 01:53:24.000
his own emotions.

01:53:25.000 --> 01:53:26.000
The same Bandura.

01:53:27.000 --> 01:53:28.000
This is the psychological situation.

01:53:29.000 --> 01:53:30.000
There are some additional characteristics.

01:53:31.000 --> 01:53:32.000
Not the psyche in the usual understanding

01:53:33.000 --> 01:53:34.000
of those same cognitivists.

01:53:35.000 --> 01:53:36.000
There are some additional

01:53:37.000 --> 01:53:38.000
psychological characteristics.

01:53:38.000 --> 01:53:39.000
There are some additional parameters

01:53:40.000 --> 01:53:41.000
of my inner variable.

01:53:42.000 --> 01:53:43.000
Desires,

01:53:44.000 --> 01:53:45.000
emotions,

01:53:46.000 --> 01:53:47.000
affections,

01:53:48.000 --> 01:53:49.000
expectations,

01:53:50.000 --> 01:53:51.000
mistakes,

01:53:52.000 --> 01:53:53.000
needs.

01:53:54.000 --> 01:53:55.000
This is the psychological situation.

01:53:56.000 --> 01:53:57.000
Again,

01:53:58.000 --> 01:53:59.000
the principle is

01:54:00.000 --> 01:54:01.000
what can be measured,

01:54:02.000 --> 01:54:03.000
what can be justified,

01:54:04.000 --> 01:54:05.000
what can be assessed.

01:54:06.000 --> 01:54:07.000
And it is not only assessed

01:54:08.000 --> 01:54:09.000
by the person himself.

01:54:10.000 --> 01:54:11.000
Here the rotor,

01:54:12.000 --> 01:54:13.000
like Bandura and Skinner,

01:54:14.000 --> 01:54:15.000
hold the same point of view.

01:54:16.000 --> 01:54:17.000
I can think whatever I want about myself.

01:54:18.000 --> 01:54:19.000
And, accordingly,

01:54:20.000 --> 01:54:21.000
it is pointless to say

01:54:22.000 --> 01:54:23.000
whether you are right or wrong.

01:54:24.000 --> 01:54:25.000
All these variables

01:54:26.000 --> 01:54:27.000
are given so that

01:54:28.000 --> 01:54:29.000
I can characterize

01:54:30.000 --> 01:54:31.000
those inner variables

01:54:32.000 --> 01:54:33.000
that move a person

01:54:34.000 --> 01:54:35.000
and through which

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:37.000
this external stimulus passes,

01:54:38.000 --> 01:54:39.000
responsible for the behavior

01:54:40.000 --> 01:54:41.000
that arises in a person.
